---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';
const bodyHtml = `<main x-data="base64ToJpeg()">
        <h1><i class="fas fa-file-image"></i> Base64 to JPEG Converter</h1>
        <p class="intro">Convert Base64 strings to JPEG images with adjustable quality</p>

        <div class="trust-note">
            <strong>🔒 Privacy First:</strong> All conversion happens locally in your browser. Your data never leaves your device.
        </div>

        <section class="tool-section">
            <div class="input-group">
                <label for="base64Input">Paste your Base64 string:</label>
                <textarea
                    id="base64Input"
                    x-model="base64Input"
                    placeholder="Paste your Base64 string here..."
                    rows="6"
                ></textarea>
                <div class="error" x-show="error" x-text="error"></div>
            </div>

            <div class="input-group">
                <label for="qualitySlider">JPEG Quality: <strong x-text="quality"></strong></label>
                <input
                    type="range"
                    id="qualitySlider"
                    x-model="quality"
                    @input="decodeImage"
                    min="0.1"
                    max="1.0"
                    step="0.01"
                    style="width: 100%;"
                >
                <small>0.1 = smallest file size &nbsp;|&nbsp; 0.92 = recommended &nbsp;|&nbsp; 1.0 = maximum quality</small>
            </div>

            <div class="actions">
                <button @click="decodeImage" class="btn-primary">Convert to JPEG</button>
                <button @click="clearAll" class="btn-secondary">Clear</button>
            </div>

            <div class="preview-container" x-show="imageUrl">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-image"></i> Preview</h2>
                <div class="image-wrapper">
                    <img :src="imageUrl" alt="Converted JPEG preview" x-show="imageUrl">
                </div>
                <div class="image-info" x-show="imageInfo">
                    <p><strong>Original Format:</strong> <span x-text="imageInfo.originalFormat"></span></p>
                    <p><strong>Output Format:</strong> JPEG</p>
                    <p><strong>Quality:</strong> <span x-text="imageInfo.quality"></span></p>
                    <p><strong>Size:</strong> <span x-text="imageInfo.size"></span></p>
                </div>
                <button @click="downloadJpeg" class="btn-primary">Download JPEG</button>
            </div>
        </section>

        <article class="content-section">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-question-circle"></i> What Is Base64 to JPEG Conversion?</h2>
            <p>
                Base64 to JPEG conversion decodes a Base64-encoded string and re-encodes the pixel data as a JPEG image file. JPEG uses lossy compression controlled by a quality parameter between 0 and 1. At the default 0.92 setting, JPEG achieves roughly 10:1 compression with minimal visible quality loss, producing files significantly smaller than lossless PNG. This tool handles the entire process client-side using the browser Canvas API.
            </p>

            <h2><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Why Convert Base64 to JPEG Format?</h2>
            <p>
                JPEG produces smaller files than PNG for photographic content. A typical photo saved as PNG may be 2-5 MB, while the same image at JPEG quality 0.92 occupies 200-500 KB. JPEG is the standard format for photographs on the web, email attachments, and social media uploads. Converting Base64 data to JPEG is useful when extracting photos from API responses, database records, or embedded data URIs where file size matters more than lossless quality. For lossless output, use the <a href="/base64-to-png/">Base64 to PNG converter</a> instead.
            </p>

            <h2><i class="fas fa-cog"></i> How Does the JPEG Converter Work?</h2>
            <p>
                The converter follows 4 steps. First, it strips any data URI prefix and validates the Base64 characters. Second, it decodes the Base64 string and loads the image data into an HTML Image element. Third, it draws the image onto an invisible Canvas element with a white background fill to replace any transparency. Fourth, it calls <code>canvas.toDataURL('image/jpeg', quality)</code> to produce JPEG output at the selected quality level. The entire process runs in your browser using native APIs.
            </p>

            <h2><i class="fas fa-table"></i> What Is the Difference Between JPEG and PNG?</h2>
            <p>
                JPEG and PNG serve different purposes. JPEG uses lossy compression optimized for photographs, while PNG uses lossless compression suited for graphics with sharp edges. The following table compares the two formats across 5 criteria.
            </p>
            <table class="reference-table">
                <thead>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Feature</th>
                        <th>JPEG</th>
                        <th>PNG</th>
                    </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Compression Type</td>
                        <td>Lossy (DCT-based)</td>
                        <td>Lossless (DEFLATE)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Transparency</td>
                        <td>Not supported</td>
                        <td>Full alpha channel</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>File Size (photo)</td>
                        <td>Small (100-500 KB)</td>
                        <td>Large (1-5 MB)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Best Use Case</td>
                        <td>Photos, gradients</td>
                        <td>Logos, text, screenshots</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Color Depth</td>
                        <td>24-bit (16.7M colors)</td>
                        <td>24-bit or 32-bit with alpha</td>
                    </tr>
                </tbody>
            </table>

            <h2><i class="fas fa-sliders-h"></i> What JPEG Quality Setting Should You Use?</h2>
            <p>
                The optimal JPEG quality depends on the output purpose. A quality of 0.92 is the default because it preserves visual fidelity while achieving meaningful compression. For web images where page load speed matters, 0.80 reduces file size by an additional 30-40% with barely perceptible quality loss. For print materials or archival storage, use 1.0 to minimize compression artifacts. Values below 0.60 produce visible blocky artifacts and should be used only when extreme file size reduction is required. The <a href="/base64-image-encoder/">Base64 image encoder</a> can encode your JPEG files back to Base64 when needed.
            </p>

            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

            <div class="faq">
                <h3>What JPEG quality setting produces the best results?</h3>
                <p>
                    A quality of 0.92 provides an optimal balance between file size and visual fidelity. Use 0.80 for web images where smaller file size matters, and 1.0 for print or archival purposes where maximum quality is required.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq">
                <h3>Does JPEG support transparency?</h3>
                <p>
                    No. JPEG does not support transparency. When converting images with transparent backgrounds, this tool fills the transparent areas with white. For transparency support, use the <a href="/base64-to-png/">PNG converter</a> or <a href="/base64-to-webp/">WebP converter</a> instead.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq">
                <h3>Can this tool create progressive JPEG files?</h3>
                <p>
                    No. The browser Canvas API generates baseline JPEG files only. Progressive JPEG encoding requires server-side tools like libjpeg. Baseline JPEGs load top-to-bottom, while progressive JPEGs load in multiple passes at increasing quality.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq">
                <h3>Does the converted JPEG retain EXIF metadata?</h3>
                <p>
                    No. The Canvas API strips all EXIF metadata during conversion, including camera settings, GPS coordinates, and orientation data. This can be a privacy benefit when sharing images online.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="faq">
                <h3>Is this tool safe for sensitive images?</h3>
                <p>
                    Yes. All conversion happens locally in your browser using the Canvas API. Your Base64 data and images never leave your device. No data is uploaded to any server. Learn more about <a href="/what-is-base64/">what Base64 encoding is</a> and how it works.
                </p>
            </div>

            <p>
                Related tools: <a href="/base64-to-png/">Base64 to PNG</a> | <a href="/base64-image-decoder/">Base64 Image Decoder</a> | <a href="/base64-image-encoder/">Base64 Image Encoder</a> | <a href="/base64-embed-generator/">Embed Generator</a> | <a href="/jpeg-to-base64/">JPEG to Base64</a> | <a href="/what-is-base64/">What Is Base64?</a>
            </p>
        </article>
    </main>`;
---
<ToolLayout
  title="Base64 to JPEG Converter - Convert Base64 to JPEG Image Online"
  description="Free online Base64 to JPEG converter. Paste your Base64 string and convert it to JPEG format with adjustable quality. Download compressed JPEG images instantly."
  canonical="https://base64image.net/base64-to-jpeg/"
  h1="Base64 to JPEG Converter"
  mono="// Canvas API"
  lede="Convert Base64 strings to JPEG images with adjustable quality"
  tag="convert"
  tagLabel="Converter"
  breadcrumbs={[{label:'Home',href:'/'},{label:'Converters',href:'#'},{label:'Base64 → JPEG'}]}
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script defer src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/alpinejs@3.x.x/dist/cdn.min.js"></script>
    <script type="application/ld+json">
    {
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "HowTo",
        "name": "How to Convert Base64 to JPEG",
        "description": "Step-by-step guide to convert Base64 strings to JPEG images online with adjustable quality",
        "step": [{
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "name": "Paste Base64 String",
            "text": "Copy your Base64 string and paste it into the text area. The data:image prefix is optional."
        }, {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "name": "Adjust JPEG Quality",
            "text": "Use the quality slider to set compression level from 0.1 (smallest file) to 1.0 (highest quality). Default is 0.92."
        }, {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "name": "Preview JPEG Image",
            "text": "View the converted JPEG image in the preview section along with file size and quality information."
        }, {
            "@type": "HowToStep",
            "name": "Download JPEG",
            "text": "Click the 'Download JPEG' button to save the image as a .jpg file to your device."
        }]
    }
        </script>
    <script type="application/ld+json">
    {
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
        "itemListElement": [{
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 1,
            "name": "Home",
            "item": "https://base64image.net/"
        }, {
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 2,
            "name": "Base64 to JPEG Converter",
            "item": "https://base64image.net/base64-to-jpeg/"
        }]
    }
        </script>
    <script type="application/ld+json">
    {
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "FAQPage",
        "mainEntity": [{
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What JPEG quality setting produces the best results?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "A quality of 0.92 provides an optimal balance between file size and visual fidelity. Use 0.80 for web images where smaller file size matters, and 1.0 for print or archival purposes where maximum quality is required."
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Does JPEG support transparency?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "No. JPEG does not support transparency. When converting images with transparent backgrounds, this tool fills the transparent areas with white. For transparency support, use PNG or WebP format instead."
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Can this tool create progressive JPEG files?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "No. The browser Canvas API generates baseline JPEG files only. Progressive JPEG encoding requires server-side tools like libjpeg. Baseline JPEGs load top-to-bottom, while progressive JPEGs load in multiple passes at increasing quality."
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Does the converted JPEG retain EXIF metadata?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "No. The Canvas API strips all EXIF metadata during conversion, including camera settings, GPS coordinates, and orientation data. This can be a privacy benefit when sharing images online."
            }
        }, {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Is this tool safe for sensitive images?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "Yes. All conversion happens locally in your browser using the Canvas API. Your Base64 data and images never leave your device. No data is uploaded to any server."
            }
        }]
    }
        </script>
  </Fragment>
  <Fragment set:html={bodyHtml} />
  <script is:inline>function base64ToJpeg() {
            return {
                base64Input: '',
                imageUrl: '',
                error: '',
                imageInfo: null,
                canvas: null,
                quality: 0.92,

                decodeImage() {
                    this.error = '';
                    this.imageUrl = '';
                    this.imageInfo = null;

                    if (!this.base64Input.trim()) {
                        return;
                    }

                    try {
                        // Strip data URI prefix if present
                        let base64String = this.base64Input.trim();
                        let originalFormat = 'unknown';
                        const dataUriMatch = base64String.match(/^data:image\/([a-zA-Z0-9+\-]+);base64,(.+)$/);

                        if (dataUriMatch) {
                            originalFormat = dataUriMatch[1];
                            base64String = dataUriMatch[2];
                        }

                        // Validate Base64
                        if (!/^[A-Za-z0-9+/]*={0,2}$/.test(base64String)) {
                            throw new Error('Invalid Base64 string. Only A-Z, a-z, 0-9, +, /, and = are allowed.');
                        }

                        // Create image from Base64
                        const img = new Image();
                        const quality = parseFloat(this.quality);
                        img.onload = () => {
                            // Create canvas and draw image
                            this.canvas = document.createElement('canvas');
                            this.canvas.width = img.width;
                            this.canvas.height = img.height;
                            const ctx = this.canvas.getContext('2d');

                            // Fill with white background (JPEG does not support transparency)
                            ctx.fillStyle = '#FFFFFF';
                            ctx.fillRect(0, 0, this.canvas.width, this.canvas.height);
                            ctx.drawImage(img, 0, 0);

                            // Get JPEG data URL
                            this.imageUrl = this.canvas.toDataURL('image/jpeg', quality);

                            // Calculate size
                            const sizeInBytes = Math.round((this.imageUrl.length - 'data:image/jpeg;base64,'.length) * 3 / 4);

                            this.imageInfo = {
                                originalFormat: originalFormat.toUpperCase(),
                                quality: quality,
                                size: this.formatBytes(sizeInBytes)
                            };
                        };
                        img.onerror = () => {
                            this.error = 'Failed to load image. Please check your Base64 string.';
                        };

                        // Try to load with original format first, fallback to generic
                        if (originalFormat !== 'unknown') {
                            img.src = `data:image/${originalFormat};base64,${base64String}`;
                        } else {
                            img.src = `data:image/png;base64,${base64String}`;
                        }

                    } catch (err) {
                        this.error = err.message || 'Failed to decode Base64 string. Please check your input.';
                        this.imageUrl = '';
                        this.imageInfo = null;
                    }
                },

                formatBytes(bytes) {
                    if (bytes === 0) return '0 Bytes';
                    const k = 1024;
                    const sizes = ['Bytes', 'KB', 'MB'];
                    const i = Math.floor(Math.log(bytes) / Math.log(k));
                    return Math.round((bytes / Math.pow(k, i)) * 100) / 100 + ' ' + sizes[i];
                },

                downloadJpeg() {
                    if (!this.imageUrl) return;

                    const timestamp = Date.now();
                    const filename = `converted-image-${timestamp}.jpg`;

                    const link = document.createElement('a');
                    link.href = this.imageUrl;
                    link.download = filename;
                    document.body.appendChild(link);
                    link.click();
                    document.body.removeChild(link);
                },

                clearAll() {
                    this.base64Input = '';
                    this.imageUrl = '';
                    this.error = '';
                    this.imageInfo = null;
                    this.canvas = null;
                    this.quality = 0.92;
                }
            }
        }</script>
</ToolLayout>
